CONCEPTUAL SPEC — the main idea of the product. Lives above all implementation specs; changes here have far-reaching consequences.

PROBLEM STATEMENT. Drift detects divergence between specifications and code. Specifications ("specs") declare intended behavior; code markers wrap the lines that implement each spec. Each spec and each marker has a content hash. When a hash changes on either side, the edge between them is "drifted" and a human or LLM agent must review before the baseline is re-established.

Specs themselves cite other specs ("See spec T for the rule this derives from"). Those citations are meaningful: if T's content changes, every spec that cites T may need re-verification. Tracking citations as first-class edges lets drift propagate correctly through the spec graph — without them, edits to a foundational spec silently invalidate every downstream spec without any signal.

THE UNIFIED EDGE. The post-collapse model has ONE edge type. An Edge is a directed relationship between two nodes (specs and/or markers). The From endpoint declares/stores the edge (the citer); the To endpoint is the target (the cited). Two establishment kinds are encoded by endpoint types:
  - marker → spec (created by `drift link`): the marker stores the edge to the spec it implements.
  - spec → spec (auto-parsed from &lt;ref spec="…"&gt; in spec text): the source spec stores the edge to the spec it references.
The establishment ceremony differs (explicit command vs ambient parse), but the storage and the drift semantics are identical. There is no separate "link" or "ref" type — they are unified under Edge.

NOTATION. We adopt a uniform notation for nodes and edges:
  $ — a spec. $1, $2, $3 are distinct specs.
  # — a marker. #A, #B are distinct markers.
  &lt; , &gt; — directed storage edges. "X &gt; Y" reads: X stores an edge pointing to Y (X is the citer, Y is the cited). "X &lt; Y" is the same edge mirrored — Y stores the edge to X.
Worked examples:
  $1 &lt; $2                 — $2 stores an edge to $1. ($2 contains &lt;ref spec="$1"&gt;.)
  $1 &lt; $2 &lt; #A           — equivalent to ($1 &lt; $2)($2 &lt; #A): $2 has an edge to $1; #A has an edge to $2.
  ($1 &lt; $2)($2 &lt; #A)($2 &lt; $300)($300 &lt; $400) — a citation cluster: $2 has one outbound edge, two inbound edges (#A via link, $300 via ref); $300 is itself pointed at by $400.

AXIOMS.
  (A1) DAG over spec-spec edges. The directed graph contains no directed cycles among spec-spec edges: $1 &gt; $2 &gt; $1 is forbidden. Cycles would make the "citer chain" notion ambiguous and break topological reasoning. Marker endpoints cannot participate in cycles because markers are always citers, never the cited (axiom A2).
  (A2) Cite asymmetry. Markers cannot be cited. A marker #A may cite a spec (#A &gt; $S) but no node may cite a marker. The single retained asymmetry between specs and markers is this: specs can be cited by both specs and markers; markers cannot be cited by anything.
  (A3) Provenance-directed propagation. Drift propagates along edges in the CITER direction (cited → citer), transitive to fixpoint. If $S changes, every node that transitively cites $S becomes drift-impacted, because each citer's alignment with $S is now suspect. Propagation does NOT flow in the cited direction: a citer's change does not invalidate the cited node's text, which is independent. Worked examples:
        - $2 &gt; $1, $1 drifts → $2 is drift-impacted (citer of $1).
        - $2 &gt; $1, $2 drifts → $1 NOT drift-impacted (cited by $2; $1's text didn't change).
        - #A &gt; $1, $1 drifts → #A is drift-impacted (citer of $1).
        - #A &gt; $1, #A drifts → $1 NOT drift-impacted via citer walk. But the marker's outgoing edge targets are added to the marker's closure so the reviewer can verify the marker still implements the linked spec.
  (A4) Marker seeds include their linked specs. When a marker #A drifts, its closure includes #A's outgoing-edge targets (the specs #A links to), so the reviewer can verify #A still implements each linked spec. From those specs, propagation walks the citer chain (cited → citer) as usual. This is the only special-case expansion; it exists because marker drift means "the implementation of these specs changed," and reviewers need the specs in scope.

ALGORITHM. Given baseline state B (hashes + edge set at last review) and scan S (hashes + edge set now):
  (i) Seed collection. Register drift events:
        - NODE_CHANGED for each baseline node whose scan hash differs from baseline hash.
        - EDGE_ADDED for each spec-spec edge in S but not in B (link edges are user-curated and never appear in scan).
        - EDGE_REMOVED for each spec-spec edge in B but not in S.
        - EDGE_BROKEN for each scan edge whose To endpoint doesn't exist as a node.
        - NODE_ADDED is implied by reconciler baseline-hash sentinel "" for new scan nodes; NODE_REMOVED by reconciler Deleted=true.
      Each event has a seed = the citer-side node where the change is observable (the changed node itself for node events; the From endpoint for edge events).
  (ii) Closure derivation. For each seed S:
         - closure_nodes = {S}.
         - If S is a marker (A4): for each baseline or scan edge where S is the From endpoint, add the To endpoint to closure_nodes.
         - BFS from every node in closure_nodes over INCOMING edges (citer walk). For each (citer, node) edge where node ∈ closure_nodes, add citer. Repeat to fixpoint.
         - closure_edges = edges among closure_nodes (undirected canonicalization: min(from,to) + separator + max(from,to)).
         - closure_hash = first 8 hex chars of SHA1(sorted node IDs + sorted undirected edge keys).
      Multiple seeds may produce closures with the same hash (rare: tightly-coupled seed pair). Such closures merge with combined events. Otherwise closures are strictly disjoint: a non-seed citer can appear in multiple closures (e.g., S3 cites both S1 and S2 — when both drift, S3 is in each closure independently).
  (iii) Cycle safety. The BFS uses a visited set; the spec-spec edge graph is a DAG by (A1), so the citer walk terminates. Cycle detection in Validate rejects directed cycles at state-load time.

CLOSURE PROPERTIES.
  - Identity = membership (8-char hash of nodes + edges). Stable across drift-state changes within the same membership; changes only when nodes/edges are added or removed.
  - Ephemeral: closures exist for the current `drift todo` run; they are not stored in state.xml.
  - Per-seed events: a closure's events are those whose seed is the closure's seed. Reset syncs only the closure's events; non-seed citers' state is unchanged.
  - Overlap on non-seed citers: a non-seed citer can be a member of multiple closures; resetting one closure does not affect another.

RESOLUTION. Each closure resolves with `drift reset &lt;hash&gt;`:
  - NODE_CHANGED on N  → baseline hash of N set to scan hash.
  - EDGE_ADDED(X, Y)   → edge added to baseline.
  - EDGE_REMOVED(X, Y) → edge removed from baseline.
  - NODE_ADDED on N    → N is already in the reconciled baseline with empty hash; reset establishes the baseline.
  - NODE_REMOVED on N  → N removed from baseline; its edges filtered out.
  - EDGE_BROKEN(X, Y)  → no-op (user must fix the scan: add the missing spec or remove the ref).
Closures containing ONLY broken-edge events are refused — the user must fix the scan first.

This spec is the contract. Implementation specs (core.validate, core.provenance_closure, scanner.ref_parsing, orch.reset_closure, pinstore.baselines) describe how the contract is realized; they may be refactored freely as long as the behavior here is preserved.